The key deliverables for this role are as follows:
• Be accountable for meeting the Home Office’s analytical requirements at strategic, operational, and in some cases tactical, level – and for ensuring analysis delivers actionable insights which improve departmental outcomes and maximise real-world impact (including publicly);
• Have responsibility for multi-disciplinary analysis and insight teams working across all areas of Home Office business, including crime, policing, fire, extremism, counter-terrorism, borders and migration;
• Lead an organisation of over 450 people through a period of significant change, including overseeing growth in areas outside London and moves to greater flexible working;
• Continue the transformation of the use of analysis and evidence in the department, while continuing to build HOAI as a centre of excellence recognised across the department, Whitehall and beyond;
• Personally champion analysis and insight, including ensuring customer support for managing competing demands from across the Home Office through an effective and transparent prioritisation process;
• Ensure professional standards in Home Office Analysis and Insight, including: rigorously maintaining the necessary degree of independence and objectivity; supporting the Home Office heads of analytical professions to meet their statutory responsibilities (e.g. for publishing statistics and signing off impact assessments); and representing the Home Office as a senior member of the cross-government analysis and insight community;
• Be accountable for professional development for Home Office economists, statisticians and operational and social researchers, at the same time as influencing investment in analysis and insight capabilities, and building the department’s expertise in emerging techniques and disciplines.
• Be the Home Office champion for the Public Sector Equality Duty, and to lead on implementing a number of analytical recommendations in the Windrush Lessons Learned Review

Responsibilities
The successful candidate will be an excellent experienced analytical leader, comfortable working with and presenting at Executive Committee level, with a breadth of experience gained whilst working to put analysis and evidence at the heart of decision making in large and complex organisations.

It is essential that in your written application
you give evidence of examples of proven
experience in each of the essential criteria
of the person specification.

Essential Criteria
• Dynamic leadership skills, including the ability to influence Ministerial/Board level and other senior thinking and decision-making, inspire change, and to set a clear direction to deliver organisational objectives;

• Strong analytical skills; and/or experience of setting direction for analytical work programmes, particularly in government settings, which directly support strategic organisational objectives, working across boundaries so that the right people are involved to deliver;

• The ability to develop actionable insights from analysis and to communicate them clearly to a wide range of customers, including Ministers/Board members, scanning the political context and taking account of wider influences to develop long term strategies to maximise the impact of analysis and insights on delivering Home Office priorities;

• Creating and sustaining a culture of innovation and continuous improvement, and supporting transformational programmes.

Desirable Criteria
• Membership of one of the four principal analytical professions (economics, operational research, social research, and statistics) and/or a good understanding of intelligence assessment or emerging analytical disciplines (e.g. data science, social media analysis, behavioural science).

Parity Group are delighted to be engaged with a well-known progressive organisation on a large project and as a result have the need for a Director of Data to join their team based in London (Remote working for now) on a 3 months contract.
ALL APPLICANTS PLEASE NOTE THAT THSI ROLE IS INSIDE IR35.
Job Description
The Director is responsible for delivering the strategy to transform the way data is managed, used and shared across government, unlocking its potential to increase efficiency, improve policy and decision- making and provide better public services. This programme of work is co-sponsored by the organisation and the Chief Operating Officer for the Civil Service. The strategy and its delivery are overseen by the Government Digital Data and Technology (DDaT) Steering Group (GDSG), a cross government ministerial group. The postholder will report directly to the Deputy National Statistician for Data Capability on these strands of work.
The Director is also responsible for the delivery of the organisations contributions to the overarching priority of improving the use of government data. This includes overall responsibility for the development and delivery of the strategy for integrated data within the the organisation, specifically as Senior Responsible Owner (SRO) for the Integrated Data Platform (IDP) programme and the partnership with Health Data Research UK (HDR UK). These two programmes are critical to delivering the cross-cutting analytical platform for government and beyond. A key element to the orgnaisations delivery is providing access to users external to government such as researchers, local government, academics and think tanks. At the centre of the integrated data strategy is working in partnership with other providers of analysis and analytical platforms, to ensure the broadest use and access to linked data.
Role Responsibilities:
Senior Responsible Owner: Government DDaT Steering Group (GDSG)
Senior Responsible Owner: Integrated Delivery Plan (IDP) Deliver the Full Business Case (FBC) and the benefits articulated therein;
Deliver the GDSG objectives to demonstrate a clear improvement in the use of data through a series of lighthouse projects;
Increase public acceptability of the use of data in government;
In partnership with HM Treasury (HMT), use Spending Review 2020 to drive improvements in the use and sharing of data across government;
Keep the GDSG informed of the current status of the programme, identifying relevant risks and issues where appropriate;
Create and deliver a coherent approach to the use of integrated data across government, including operational and analytical data, aligning relevant data initiatives in departments;
Stakeholder engagement and communications to build cross-government support for improving the use of data;
Ensure coherent, overarching narrative for government data in seeking funding through the Spending Review, budget, programme business cases etc;
Develop the strategic approach to delivery, including the delivery plan;
Ensure IDP delivers required elements to support the GDSG objectives;
Ensure delivery of lighthouse projects within the programme both addresses systemic blockers and delivers innovative analytical outcomes.
Deliver, in partnership with HDR UK, the integrated data required to support the COVID National Core Studies, creating the foundations for a health data system for the UK;
Navigate Whitehall to develop excellent cross-government relationships with senior stakeholders across government, including Ministers, Chief Scientific Advisers, Chief Data Officers, Cabinet Office, HMT, policy leads and the wider analytical community to build influential coalition to deliver the improved use of data across government.
